Welcome properly aboard iteration 19, then. Everything you asked for is done and verified in a live render; here's the tour.

**Photos (assets/).** The six are now `PAKO1.jpg`…`PAKO6.jpg` (in the original numbering order: 4466→1, 4470→2, 4471→3, 4479→4, 4480→5, 4481→6); the PAKO44xx originals are deleted as agreed.
- PAKO2 and PAKO3 (old 4470/4471) are flipped horizontally, so all six now face right.
- Those two had the jeans cropped off with a similarity crop: the bottom edge sits just above the first denim pixel, and the sides/top are trimmed by the matching proportion so your relative placement in the frame (head margin, horizontal position) is conserved — the same framing, just tighter. Heads-up: **PAKO1 (old 4466) also had a one-percent sliver of jeans at its very bottom edge** — I trimmed it the same conserve-placement way.
- The "black artifacts": good news — they're not a poor black scale. They are **resampling moiré**: the shop delivered 4479/80/81 already downscaled (~0.79× — the EXIF still declares the original 4480px size), and rescaling a regular piqué weave near its own frequency bakes in those conical interference bands, which your viewer's second rescale then amplifies. So the cure was to re-derive the small files cleanly: a prefiltered, properly anti-aliased downscale, plus a gentle amplitude-capped smoothing of that frequency band on the dark shirt only (folds and edges untouched). Verified under a 3.6× shadow boost: no bands, texture intact.
- All six are 1600px tall (~150–250 KB, down from 3–8 MB), quality 90, no chroma subsampling, EXIF stripped (it carried camera and Photoshop traces). 1600px covers a QHD screen at full height; if you can tell the difference on your monitor, say so and I'll re-derive at a higher target — the pipeline is scripted.

**The portrait.** `index.html` now points at `assets/portrait.jpg`, a symlink to **PAKO4** (the closed, confident smile — my pick for a look-competent page; 5 and 6 grin wider). Swapping = repointing that symlink to any other PAKOn. The frame is now 3:4 (the shop-crop aspect) with the image top-anchored, so the full-length shots crop at the bottom, never your head.

**1 · Overlay drift — root-caused and fixed.** The gold layer is rasterised with canvas `fillText`, and canvas ignores CSS `letter-spacing` — your name has 0.02em of it. So the raster came out narrower than the DOM text and drifted open along the word: 'J' fine, 'ATAN' worse — exactly both your captures. reflect.js now (a) sets the canvas's own letterSpacing from the computed style, and (b) pins both ends regardless: each word's raster is scaled onto its real DOM rect width, so no engine quirk can ever open a gap along a word again. Verified with a point mid-'JONATAN': perfect registration.

**2 · Bars now light like ink.** The bar was rasterised as a flat rectangle, and the shader lights by edge normals — a flat interior is a dead plateau, so only the top edge ever answered. It's now rasterised as an ink-profiled stroke (full coverage in the core, soft shoulders on the long edges, rounded ends), which is exactly what a glyph stem looks like to the shader. A point near a bar now blooms a warm gold hotspot along the bar's whole body — same effect and colour as the 'O'.

**4+5 · One official gold, and the "colder logo" solved.** The site had two yellows: `#fad02a` (your clicked-JONATAN gold, the annulus peak) and a paler `#ffe666` dressing the headers, chips, dots and glow. `#fad02a` is now `--gold`, official: section headers, the contact heading, publication accents, language levels, chips, focus rings — everything ink-side. Your point-5 diagnosis was right on both counts: the maxed annulus was already the clicked gold, and the cold feel came from how the in-between levels were made — the annulus faded flat gold by transparency, which passes through washed-out olive. All partial illumination now mixes gold with black along the warm ember ramp the ring letters already used (dark → amber → `#fad02a`): the annulus bands, the b faces, and the text shader itself. Half-lit reads warm everywhere now.

**7 · Barreiro is one word.** Its three spans (split around the i-dot anchor) now share a word group: clicking or selecting any piece turns the whole surname gold at once. General rule — any word split by inline markup behaves as a unit.

**3+5 · The 3×2 source collection.** In `sources/iteration19/` there are six runnable folders:
`interaction_2026_07_02_{bgwhite,bgalabaster,bgparchment}_{glowcool,glowwarm}/`
- **bgwhite** `#fefefe` — the exact studio white of the photos (I sampled it; the photo melts into the page);
- **bgalabaster** — the current `#f5f4f1`;
- **bgparchment** `#ece7dc` — my bet: a deeper warm neutral that makes the photo read as a lit object and gives the gold real ground to glow on;
- **glowcool** `#ffe666` (current ambient) vs **glowwarm** `#fad02a` (the glow becomes the gold).
They share the live source by symlink and differ only in `styles.css` — the ambient colour now lives in `--glow`/`--glow-rgb`, which main.js reads at start, so a build is two CSS lines. The live root stays bgalabaster+glowcool until you pick.

**6 · Housekeeping.** README's milestones link fixed (it still pointed at features.md); CLAUDE.md's turn label is now `Claude Fable 5` (with a note that logs through session 0017 say Claude 4.8); `contents.txt` documents the raster pinning, the bar ink profile, the word groups and the official gold; dead CSS removed (`.btn`, `.todo`, the three unpicked language presentations, `.skills__sub`, the styleless `band--tint` classes). Untouched: milestones.md (yours), the archives, and the `cv.pdf` symlink — it's referenced nowhere in the page, but I left it in case a CV-download element is still planned; say the word and I'll drop it.

**Ideas you asked for.**
- Photo integration: the most in-aesthetic move I see is giving the photo the same treatment as the bars — rasterise its thin ink frame into the reflective mask, so points light the frame like text and the photo belongs to the lighting system instead of floating on it. Cheap to do. The stronger (riskier) move: cut the background out entirely and let your figure sit directly on the page, the base fading into the vignette — worth one variant someday.
- On bgwhite: matching the studio white costs the page most of its vignette depth — you'll see it in the variant. That's partly why my bet went darker, not lighter.

The iteration stays open. When you've played with the six sources, tell me the pair to fold in (and whether PAKO4 stays as the face).


