**3 · The bars are straightened b's.** Thickness = the b's ribbon (10.5 primitive units at the logo's scale ≈ .2875em at the new kicker size). Each end wears the b's top tip taken from the real bb.svg corners: hook up on the left, hook down on the right — the 180° twin, like the monogram's own pair. The ink is a single clip-path; the lighting is your three superimposed gold layers — left tip 4-gon, thin rectangle, right tip 4-gon — with hairline seams between them so the joints read. Section names nudged 1.8rem → 2rem to carry the thicker bar.

**4 · The unrolling-b milestone — my case.** FOR: it's the strongest cohesion gesture available to the site — the bars stop imitating b's and become them, and the joint machinery (the dissection, the corners, the exact geometry) already exists in bb.txt, so the animation is a handful of rigid rotations, computationally near-free. It also completes a story the site already tells: the logo rolls with scroll; a b unrolling INTO the page furniture speaks the same voice. And your own formulation defuses the whitespace worry: present the rigid moves constrained to the Y-range of the lying b — start the roll partially straightened and clip to the bar's strip, and the layout never grows. AGAINST: six sections × an animated ornament risks demoting the effect from delightful to busy — the static tips already whisper the idea, and restraint is part of the site's look; scroll-linked animation is the classic jank source on software-compositing machines (the kind that bit us in iteration 17); and the intermediate states — a half-straightened b — may read as a glitch to a first-time visitor, where the finished bar is self-explanatory. My verdict: prototype it on ONE section only, inside the bar's strip, and let that decide; if it doesn't sing on 'about', the tips already carry it. Milestone added in three phrasings.

